                            <p>
                                So, here is my second post about <em>Coronavirus</em> data. A lot of people have asked
                                me why I am doing these statics. The reason is that I started reviewing these same
                                graphs in the financial times at <a
                                    href="https://www.ft.com/coronavirus-latest">https://www.ft.com/coronavirus-latest</a>.
                                This work is being done by <a href="https://twitter.com/jburnmurdoch">John
                                    Burn-Murdoch</a>. I though it was a very interesting data, but unfortunately if you
                                are not from UK, Italy, Spain, China or US, the rest of the graphs are too small to
                                really get to any conclusion. For me the two countries that worry me are <b>Poland</b>
                                and <b>Mexico</b>. All the data that I am presenting comes from <a
                                    href="https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/">Worldmeters</a>. This site has
                                been tracking the coronavirus data since the beginning of the outbreak. Remember these
                                graphs are being updated daily. Here are my conclusion to what I can see on the 2nd of
                                May of 2020.
                            </p>
