                            <h3 class="text-brand">#Zostanwdomu Poland</h3>

                            <p>
                                For me the total cases graph is not that important. We know that every day it passes
                                this graph will increase, so that is not important. The two things that are important is
                                how fast and in what amount. For that <b><a href="https://twitter.com/jburnmurdoch">John
                                        Burn-Murdoch</a></b> suggests that the best metric is to see the <b>New Cases
                                    Per Day in a Seven Day Rolling Average</b>, this way you eliminate the “noises”,
                                that some countries don’t report the same on weekday than weekends, and other possible
                                variations. This is really the graph that we are targeting to flattening. Right now, on
                                the Poland graph it can be seen that the tendency is to be flat at 400 cases per day in
                                average. As you can see to get it reduce is very hard, in 18 days the average increase
                                from 66 to 431, but 23 days that curve has not been able to reduce. This is graph that
                                would tell government if the <em>unlock</em> decisions are being done in a proper matter
                                or if the <em>social distancing</em> needs to be enforced. The only question I have in
                                Poland is that testing is being done in a very <em>"linear"</em> mode. In average 12,000
                                test are being done per day so it is normal to see the same amount of confirmed cases
                                every day. I think here the testing needs to increase also <em>"exponential"</em>.
                                Finally, the testing, South Korea has been the <em>"benchmark"</em> on testing, they are
                                doing 12,240 test per 1M of the population, <b>Poland</b> is at 9,671, still far from
                                Korea.
                            </p>
