                            <h3 class="text-brand">#QuedateEnCasa Mexico</h3>
                            <p>
                                Now let’s go to my beloved <b>Mexico</b>. Here the news are not as good as the
                                government has been trying to tell the people. You can see the <b>New Cases per Day in a
                                    Seven Day Rolling Average Graph</b> is still going up. Mexico has an average of
                                <b>1,300</b> cases per day. This is huge if you consider that testing is the
                                <em>lowest</em> of the OECD countries. This means that with a few testing’s we are
                                having a lot of cases. <b>Mexico</b> has <b>707</b>cases per 1M of population, that
                                sounds ridiculous compared to the 12,240 of Korea or the <b>3,000</b> of
                                <em>Ecuador</em>. I understand the government and the people what the <em>economy</em>
                                to open, but I guess is better to tell the true to the people that to lie to them. My
                                advice would be, yes we need to open the economy but our data is not showing a good
                                trend, let’s keep the vulnerable at their houses, we will increase the testing to keep
                                the <em>sick</em> in quarantine, and everybody please increase the <b>social
                                    distancing</b> measures at maximum. Increase the hygiene, wash your hand and cover
                                mouth, nose and eyes when being outside your house.
                            </p>
